  "editorial": {
    "title": "Assign Cookies: From Brute Force to Greedy Optimality",
    "intuition": "When each child has a minimum cookie size they’re willing to accept, the problem reduces to pairing the smallest possible cookie with each child in order of increasing greed. Sorting both lists and walking through them once captures exactly the maximum number of satisfiable children, because any larger cookie would only waste potential matches for less greedy children.",
    "bruteForce": "A straightforward brute‑force approach would try every subset of children and every subset of cookies, checking all possible assignments. This exhaustive search has factorial or exponential complexity, far beyond the limits of 10^5 elements. Even a simple nested loop that, for each child, scans all cookies to find a match would be O(n·m), which is too slow for the given constraints.",
    "betterSolution": "The key observation is that a child’s satisfaction depends only on whether a cookie meets or exceeds their greed. If we process children from the least greedy to the most greedy, and always give them the smallest cookie that satisfies them, we never block a later child from getting a cookie that could have satisfied them. This greedy strategy can be implemented by sorting both arrays and using two pointers to scan them once.",
    "optimalSolution": "Sort the children’s greed array and the cookies’ sizes array. Initialise two indices i and j at 0. While both indices are within bounds, if cookies[j] ≥ children[i] we count a match and advance both i and j; otherwise we advance j only. The number of matches counted is the maximum number of children that can be satisfied. This algorithm runs in O(n log n + m log m) time due to sorting and uses O(n + m) additional space for the arrays.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "Consider any optimal assignment. Sort children by greed; any child with smaller greed can only be matched to a cookie that is at least as large as theirs. If we give a child the smallest cookie that satisfies them, we leave all larger cookies available for later, more greedy children. Suppose the greedy algorithm fails to match a child that could be matched in some optimal solution. That would mean the algorithm assigned a cookie to a more greedy child that could have taken a smaller cookie, violating the minimality of the greedy choice. By induction over the sorted order, the greedy algorithm never reduces the number of possible matches, so it achieves the optimum.",
    "dryRun": "Example: children=[1,2,3], cookies=[2,3,4]. Sorted lists are the same. i=0,j=0: 2≥1 → match (cnt=1), i=1,j=1. 3≥2 → match (cnt=2), i=2,j=2. 4≥3 → match (cnt=3). All children satisfied. If cookies were [1,2], the algorithm would match only two children, which is optimal.",
    "commonMistakes": [
      "Assuming a child can take any cookie regardless of size; ignoring the greed constraint leads to overcounting.",
      "Using a single pass without sorting, which fails when children and cookies are unsorted.",
      "Choosing the largest available cookie for a child instead of the smallest, which can block later children.",
      "Implementing the two‑pointer loop incorrectly (e.g., incrementing both indices when the cookie is too small).",
      "Not handling the case where one list is exhausted before the other, causing index errors.",
      "Misinterpreting the problem as a maximum bipartite matching and overcomplicating the solution."
    ],
    "timeComplexity": "O(n log n + m log m)",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(n + m)"
  },
